2 Data imput and manipulation

dados <- read.csv("data_Miranda_et_al_2021_final.csv", sep = ";")
tree <- read.tree("arvore_calibrada.tre")

tree <- multi2di(tree)
tree$edge.length[tree$edge.length == 0] <- 0.01
tree<-phangorn::nnls.tree(cophenetic(tree),tree,rooted=TRUE) 
tree <-makeNodeLabel(tree,prefix="n")

# Create a new column with species names matching tree names format
dados <- dados %>% mutate(Species_phylo = paste(substr(Species, 1, 1), 
                                                sub("^\\w+\\s(\\w+).*", "\\1", Species),
                                                sep = "_"))
# Create dataset
data_fem <- dados %>% 
  filter(Sex == "F") %>% # Filter for females present in the phylogenetic tree
  group_by(Species, Sex) %>% 
  mutate(Mean_Carapace_width = mean(Carapace_width), # Get mean values for the other traits (needed for body shape)
         Mean_Pedipald_femur_length = mean(Pedipald_femur_length),
         Mean_Pedipald_patella_length = mean(Pedipald_patella_length)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  dplyr::select(Species, Species_phylo, N_individuals, Mean_Carapace_length, SE_Carapace_length, Mean_Carapace_width, Mean_Pedipald_femur_length, Mean_Pedipald_patella_length, Habit, Temp_mean, Temp_seasonality, Temp_range, Precip_annual, Precip_seasonality, meanLongitude, meanLatitude, Realm) %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  group_by(Species) %>% slice_head() %>% ungroup() %>% # See "TODO" below
  mutate(Habit = ifelse(Habit == "nest", "forest", Habit)) # We transformed nest to forest because we only have one

# Wich species are in the phylogeny but missing in our dataset?

3.4 Question 1: Is mean body size different among habits?

# Full model
pgls_hab <- gls(log(Mean_Carapace_length) ~ Habit, 
                cor=corPagel(1, tree, form = ~ Species_phylo),
                data=data_fem)
plot(pgls_hab) # Is this reliable?

# Is habitat related to body size?
result<-anova(pgls_hab) #aqui parou de aparecer o valor de p nessa visualiza√ß√£o '-' 
result
## Denom. DF: 66 
##             numDF  F-value p-value

## [1] 0.5240361

Result 1: Body size is marginally linked to species habits. Apparently, the differece is driven by cave species vs forest species (see below).

# Plot estimates
sjPlot::plot_model(pgls_hab)

3.6 Question 3. Which macroevolutionary model is the best explanation for whip-spider body size variation?

3.6.0.1 3.1. Including fossil as root prior (fitcontinuousMCMC)

bs_ws <- setNames(data_fem$Mean_Carapace_length, data_fem$Species_phylo) # Vector of body sizes with species names

# We used the SE of Charinus bonaldoi (0.09526254) as the fossil SE (C_bonaldoi has the highest number of individuals measured)

# A. Brownian motion

fitContinuousMCMC(tree, bs_ws, model = "BM", Ngens = 10000, sampleFreq =100, printFreq = 100, root.prior = c(3.8, 0.09526254, "normal"), outputName ="whip_BM")

bm.res <- read.table("whip_BM_model_params.txt", header= TRUE)
#head(bm.res)

# B. BM with a directional trend
fitContinuousMCMC(tree, bs_ws, model = "Trend", Ngens = 10000, sampleFreq =100, printFreq = 100, root.prior = c(3.8, 0.09526254, "normal"), outputName ="whip_Trend")
trend.res <- read.table("whip_Trend_model_params.txt", header= TRUE)
#head(trend.res)

# C. Single stationary peak, or single-optimum
fitContinuousMCMC(tree, bs_ws, model = "SSP", Ngens = 10000, sampleFreq =100, printFreq = 100, root.prior = c(3.8, 0.09526254, "normal"), outputName ="whip_SSP")

SSP.res <- read.table("whip_SSP_model_params.txt", header= TRUE)
#head(SSP.res)

# D. Accelerating-Decelerating evolution where the change in rate is exponential with respect to time
fitContinuousMCMC(tree, bs_ws, model = "ACDC.exp", Ngens = 10000, sampleFreq =100, printFreq = 100, root.prior = c(3.8, 0.09526254, "normal"), outputName ="whip_ACDC_exp")

ACDC.exp.res <- read.table("whip_ACDC_exp_model_params.txt", header= TRUE)
#head(ACDC.exp.res)

# E. Accelerating-Decelerating evolution where the change in rate is linear with respect to time
fitContinuousMCMC(tree, bs_ws, model = "ACDC.lin", Ngens = 10000, sampleFreq =100, printFreq = 100, root.prior = c(3.8, 0.09526254, "normal"), outputName ="whip_ACDC_lin")

ACDC.lin.res <- read.table("whip_ACDC_lin_model_params.txt", header= TRUE)
#head(ACDC.lin.res)

Produce trace plots of logLk scores

{

     ylim = c(min(bm.res$logLk), max = max(trend.res$logLk)))

lines(ACDC.exp.res$generation, ACDC.exp.res$logLk, col = "darkgreen")
lines(ACDC.lin.res$generation, ACDC.lin.res$logLk, col = "darkorange")

legend("bottomright", c("bm", "trend", "ssp", "ACDC.exp", "ACDC.lin"), lwd = 3, col = c("black", "red", "blue", "darkgreen", "darkorange"))
}

Remove burn-in and get Akaike‚Äôs Information Criterion (AIC) for each model

# A. Brownian motion
bm.AIC <- bm.res %>% 
  filter(generation >= 4000) %>% # Remove burn-in
  dplyr::select("logLk") %>% 
  as_vector() %>% 
  aicm()

# B. BM with a directional trend
trend.AIC <- trend.res %>% 
  filter(generation >= 4000) %>% # Remove burn-in
  dplyr::select("logLk") %>% 
  as_vector() %>% 
  aicm()

# C. Single stationary peak, or single-optimum
SSP.AIC <- SSP.res %>% 
  filter(generation >= 4000) %>% # Remove burn-in
  dplyr::select("logLk") %>% 
  as_vector() %>% 
  aicm()

# D. ACDC.exp
ACDC.exp.AIC <- ACDC.exp.res %>% 
  filter(generation >= 4000) %>% # Remove burn-in
  dplyr::select("logLk") %>% 
  as_vector() %>% 
  aicm()

#E. ACDC.lin
ACDC.lin.AIC <- ACDC.lin.res %>% 
  filter(generation >= 4000) %>% # Remove burn-in
  dplyr::select("logLk") %>% 
  as_vector() %>% 
  aicm()

# AIC values
mods <- data.frame(Model = c("Brownian motion (BM)", "BM with a directional trend", "Single stationary peak", "ACDC exponential", "ACDC linear"),
                   AIC = c(bm.AIC, trend.AIC, SSP.AIC, ACDC.exp.AIC, ACDC.lin.AIC)) %>% 
  arrange(AIC)

## Akaike weights
mods_vector <- setNames(mods$AIC, mods$Model)
aicw(mods_vector)
